[[File:Takaku shrine - Oiso Kanagawa - 2023 June 3 various 16 04 25 116000.jpeg|thumb|250px|Torii and approach path (2023 June)]]

'''Takaku Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高来神社}}, also known as '''Koma Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高麗神社}}) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Ōiso Town|ja|大磯町}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県}}, Japan. The shrine holds the status of an {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社}} (former district shrine).

The name "Takaku" is said to originate from the arrival of settlers from {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗}}, an ancient kingdom on the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島}}.<ref>Pronunciation from {{ill|Wu Chinese|ja|呉語}}, {{ill|Southern Min|ja|閩南語}}, and {{ill|Cantonese|ja|広東語}}: kau-le, kau-lâi (ko-lâi), ko-lòi, etc.</ref>

== History ==
The exact founding date is unknown, but records claim it was established during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}.

The shrine was once located at the summit of {{ill|Mount Koma (Kanagawa)|ja|高麗山}}, where it was known as '''Koma Gongen Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高麗権現社}}). To its right was {{ill|Hakusan Gongen|ja|白山権現}}, and to its left stood {{ill|Bishamonten|ja|毘沙門天}}. Together, these were known as the '''Koma Sansha Gongen''' (Three Shrines of Koma).

The shrine is closely linked to the migration of {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗}} people led by {{ill|Prince Jakko (Koma Wakaikō)|ja|高麗若光}}, who settled in {{ill|Sagami Province|ja|相模国}} after the fall of their kingdom. The shrine's festival, known as "Mifune Matsuri" (Boat Festival), includes a song referencing the "Protector of Koma" who became the guardian of {{ill|Ōiso Bay|ja|大磯浦}}.<ref>[http://www.town.oiso.kanagawa.jp/isotabi/taiken_asobu/powerspot/takakukomayama.html 高来神社(高麗神社) ・ 高麗山] (Ōiso Town)</ref>

The shrine was also a center of samurai devotion. {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝}} is said to have prayed here for the safe childbirth of his wife, {{ill|Hōjō Masako|ja|北条政子}}. During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代}}, the {{ill|Later Hōjō clan|ja|後北条氏}} donated a small piece of land to the shrine.

The shrine stands in the former village of {{ill|Koma Village|ja|高麗村}}, later incorporated into {{ill|Ōiso Town|ja|大磯町}}.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* {{ill|Kami-Musubi-no-Kami|ja|神皇産霊尊}}
* {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja|天津彦穂邇々伎尊}}
* {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇}}
* {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后}}

== Timeline ==
* Reign of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}: Claimed founding era
* Reign of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇}}: Kami-Musubi and Ninigi-no-Mikoto enshrined
* 533 AD (Reign of {{ill|Emperor Ankan|ja|安閑天皇}}): Empress Jingū and Emperor Ōjin enshrined
* 717 AD (Yōrō 1): Shrine becomes a Buddhist temple complex under {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}}
* 1591 AD (Tenshō 19): Receives a land grant (100 koku) from the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府}}
* 1868 AD (Meiji 1): Becomes solely a Shinto shrine ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離}})
* 1873 AD (Meiji 6): Ranked as {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社}} (district shrine)
* 1897 AD (Meiji 30): Renamed to '''Takaku Shrine''' after the nearby historical district of {{ill|Takaku-gō|ja|高来郷}}
* 1907 AD (Meiji 40): Designated as a shrine for imperial offerings

== Annual Festivals ==
* '''New Year's Festival''' (元旦祭): January 1  
* '''Setsubun Festival''' (節分祭): February 3  
* '''Spring Festival''' (春季festival): Closest weekend to April 18  
** Includes a procession ({{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿}}) from the upper shrine to the main shrine  
* '''Summer Grand Festival''' (夏季大祭): Closest Sunday to July 18  
** Known as the "{{ill|Ofune Matsuri|ja|御船祭}}" (Boat Festival) on even-numbered years  

== Access ==
* {{ill|JR East|ja|東日本旅客鉄道}} {{ill|Tōkaidō Main Line (JR East)|ja|東海道本線}}: From {{ill|Ōiso Station|ja|大磯駅}}, take the bus toward {{ill|Hiratsuka Station|ja|平塚駅}} North Exit and alight at "Kesho-zaka" or "Hanamizu" bus stop (3 minutes on foot).

