[[File:Takaku shrine - Oiso Kanagawa - 2023 June 3 various 16 04 25 116000.jpeg|thumb|250px|Torii and approach path (2023 June)]]

'''Takaku Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高来神社}}, also known as '''Koma Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高麗神社}}) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Ōiso Town|ja|大磯町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōiso Town|qq=}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanagawa Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. The shrine holds the status of an {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}} (former district shrine).

The name "Takaku" is said to originate from the arrival of settlers from {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goguryeo|qq=}}, an ancient kingdom on the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Korean Peninsula|qq=}}.<ref>Pronunciation from {{ill|Wu Chinese|ja|呉語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wu Chinese|qq=}}, {{ill|Southern Min|ja|閩南語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Southern Min|qq=}}, and {{ill|Cantonese|ja|広東語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cantonese|qq=}}: kau-le, kau-lâi (ko-lâi), ko-lòi, etc.</ref>

== History ==
The exact founding date is unknown, but records claim it was established during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Jimmu|qq=}}.

The shrine was once located at the summit of {{ill|Mount Koma (Kanagawa)|ja|高麗山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Koma (Kanagawa)|qq=}}, where it was known as '''Koma Gongen Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|高麗権現社}}). To its right was {{ill|Hakusan Gongen|ja|白山権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan Gongen|qq=}}, and to its left stood {{ill|Bishamonten|ja|毘沙門天|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bishamonten|qq=}}. Together, these were known as the '''Koma Sansha Gongen''' (Three Shrines of Koma).

The shrine is closely linked to the migration of {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goguryeo|qq=}} people led by {{ill|Prince Jakko (Koma Wakaikō)|ja|高麗若光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Jakko (Koma Wakaikō)|qq=}}, who settled in {{ill|Sagami Province|ja|相模国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sagami Province|qq=}} after the fall of their kingdom. The shrine's festival, known as "Mifune Matsuri" (Boat Festival), includes a song referencing the "Protector of Koma" who became the guardian of {{ill|Ōiso Bay|ja|大磯浦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōiso Bay|qq=}}.<ref>[http://www.town.oiso.kanagawa.jp/isotabi/taiken_asobu/powerspot/takakukomayama.html 高来神社(高麗神社) ・ 高麗山] (Ōiso Town)</ref>

The shrine was also a center of samurai devotion. {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} is said to have prayed here for the safe childbirth of his wife, {{ill|Hōjō Masako|ja|北条政子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōjō Masako|qq=}}. During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, the {{ill|Later Hōjō clan|ja|後北条氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Later Hōjō clan|qq=}} donated a small piece of land to the shrine.

The shrine stands in the former village of {{ill|Koma Village|ja|高麗村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koma Village|qq=}}, later incorporated into {{ill|Ōiso Town|ja|大磯町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōiso Town|qq=}}.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* {{ill|Kami-Musubi-no-Kami|ja|神皇産霊尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kami-Musubi-no-Kami|qq=}}
* {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja|天津彦穂邇々伎尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninigi-no-Mikoto|qq=}}
* {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ōjin|qq=}}
* {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Jingū|qq=}}

== Timeline ==
* Reign of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Jimmu|qq=}}: Claimed founding era
* Reign of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Suinin|qq=}}: Kami-Musubi and Ninigi-no-Mikoto enshrined
* 533 AD (Reign of {{ill|Emperor Ankan|ja|安閑天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ankan|qq=}}): Empress Jingū and Emperor Ōjin enshrined
* 717 AD (Yōrō 1): Shrine becomes a Buddhist temple complex under {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu-shūgō|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=}}
* 1591 AD (Tenshō 19): Receives a land grant (100 koku) from the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa shogunate|qq=}}
* 1868 AD (Meiji 1): Becomes solely a Shinto shrine ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}})
* 1873 AD (Meiji 6): Ranked as {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}} (district shrine)
* 1897 AD (Meiji 30): Renamed to '''Takaku Shrine''' after the nearby historical district of {{ill|Takaku-gō|ja|高来郷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takaku-gō|qq=}}
* 1907 AD (Meiji 40): Designated as a shrine for imperial offerings

== Annual Festivals ==
* '''New Year's Festival''' (元旦祭): January 1  
* '''Setsubun Festival''' (節分祭): February 3  
* '''Spring Festival''' (春季festival): Closest weekend to April 18  
** Includes a procession ({{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikoshi|qq=}}) from the upper shrine to the main shrine  
* '''Summer Grand Festival''' (夏季大祭): Closest Sunday to July 18  
** Known as the "{{ill|Ofune Matsuri|ja|御船祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ofune Matsuri|qq=}}" (Boat Festival) on even-numbered years  

== Access ==
* {{ill|JR East|ja|東日本旅客鉄道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR East|qq=}} {{ill|Tōkaidō Main Line (JR East)|ja|東海道本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkaidō Main Line (JR East)|qq=}}: From {{ill|Ōiso Station|ja|大磯駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōiso Station|qq=}}, take the bus toward {{ill|Hiratsuka Station|ja|平塚駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiratsuka Station|qq=}} North Exit and alight at "Kesho-zaka" or "Hanamizu" bus stop (3 minutes on foot).

